# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-parquet-format
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The core of Apache Hadoop consists of a storage part, known as Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS), and a processing part which is a MapReduce programming model.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Hadoop splits files into large blocks and distributes them across nodes in a cluster.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] It then transfers packaged code into nodes to process the data in parallel.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] This approach takes advantage of data locality, where nodes manipulate the data they have access to.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] This allows the dataset to be processed faster and more efficiently than it would be in a more conventional supercomputer architecture that relies on a parallel file system where computation and data are distributed via high-speed networking.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Apache Hadoop's MapReduce and HDFS components were inspired by Google papers on MapReduce and Google File System.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop framework itself is mostly written in the Java programming language, with some native code in C and command line utilities written as shell scripts.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Perl language can be easily used with Hadoop Streaming to implement the map and reduce parts of the user's program.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] According to its co-founders, Doug Cutting and Mike Cafarella, the idea of Hadoop was conceived in the Google File System paper that was published in October 2003.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The concept was extended in the Google paper *"MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters".* Development started on the Apache Nutch project, but was moved to the new Hadoop subproject in January 2006.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Doug Cutting, who was working at Yahoo! at the time, named it after his son's toy elephant.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The initial code that was factored out of Nutch consisted of about 5,000 lines of code for HDFS and about 6,000 lines of code for MapReduce.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] In March 2006, Owen O'Malley was the first committer to add to the Hadoop project; Hadoop 0.1.0 was released in April 2006.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] It continues to evolve through contributions that are being made to the project.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The first design document for the Hadoop Distributed File System was written by Dhruba Borthakur in 2007.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Hadoop consists of the *Hadoop Common* package, which provides file system and operating system level abstractions, a MapReduce engine (either MapReduce/MR1 or YARN/MR2) and the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS).
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop Common package contains the Java Archive (JAR) files and scripts needed to start Hadoop.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] For effective scheduling of work, every Hadoop-compatible file system should provide location awareness, which is the name of the rack, specifically the network switch where a worker node is.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Hadoop applications can use this information to execute code on the node where the data is, and, failing that, on the same rack/switch to reduce backbone traffic.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] HDFS uses this method when replicating data for data redundancy across multiple racks.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] This approach reduces the impact of a rack power outage or switch failure; if any of these hardware failures occurs, the data will remain available.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] A small Hadoop cluster includes a single master and multiple worker nodes.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The master node consists of a Job Tracker, Task Tracker, NameNode, and DataNode.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] A slave or *worker node* acts as both a DataNode and TaskTracker, though it is possible to have data-only and compute-only worker nodes.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] These are normally used only in nonstandard applications.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Hadoop requires the Java Runtime Environment (JRE) 1.6 or higher.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The standard startup and shutdown scripts require that Secure Shell (SSH) be set up between nodes in the cluster.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] In a larger cluster, HDFS nodes are managed through a dedicated NameNode server to host the file system index, and a secondary NameNode that can generate snapshots of the namenode's memory structures, thereby preventing file-system corruption and loss of data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Similarly, a standalone JobTracker server can manage job scheduling across nodes.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop MapReduce is used with an alternate file system, the NameNode, secondary NameNode, and DataNode architecture of HDFS are replaced by the file-system-specific equivalents.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The *Hadoop distributed file system* (HDFS) is a distributed, scalable, and portable file system written in Java for the Hadoop framework.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] A Hadoop instance is divided into HDFS and MapReduce.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] HDFS is used for storing the data and MapReduce is used for processing data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Top three are Master Services/Daemons/Nodes and bottom two are Slave Services.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Master Services can communicate with each other and in the same way Slave services can communicate with each other.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Name Node is a master node and Data node is its corresponding Slave node and can talk with each other.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Hadoop cluster has nominally a single namenode plus a cluster of datanodes, although redundancy options are available for the namenode due to its criticality.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Each datanode serves up blocks of data over the network using a block protocol specific to HDFS.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The file system uses TCP/IP sockets for communication.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Clients use remote procedure calls (RPC) to communicate with each other.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] HDFS stores large files (typically in the range of gigabytes to terabytes) across multiple machines.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] It achieves reliability by replicating the data across multiple hosts, and hence theoretically does not require redundant array of independent disks (RAID) storage on hosts (but to increase input-output (I/O) performance some RAID configurations are still useful).
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] With the default replication value, 3, data is stored on three nodes: two on the same rack, and one on a different rack.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Data nodes can talk to each other to rebalance data, to move copies around, and to keep the replication of data high.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] HDFS is not fully POSIX-compliant, because the requirements for a POSIX file-system differ from the target goals of a Hadoop application.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The trade-off of not having a fully POSIX-compliant file-system is increased performance for data throughput and support for non-POSIX operations such as Append.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] In May 2012, high-availability capabilities were added to HDFS, letting the main metadata server called the NameNode manually fail-over onto a backup.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The project has also started developing automatic fail-overs.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The HDFS file system includes a so-called *secondary namenode*, a misleading term that some might incorrectly interpret as a backup namenode when the primary namenode goes offline.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] In fact, the secondary namenode regularly connects with the primary namenode and builds snapshots of the primary namenode's directory information, which the system then saves to local or remote directories.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] These checkpointed images can be used to restart a failed primary namenode without having to replay the entire journal of file-system actions, then to edit the log to create an up-to-date directory structure.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Because the namenode is the single point for storage and management of metadata, it can become a bottleneck for supporting a huge number of files, especially a large number of small files.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] HDFS Federation, a new addition, aims to tackle this problem to a certain extent by allowing multiple namespaces served by separate namenodes.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Moreover, there are some issues in HDFS such as small file issues, scalability problems, Single Point of Failure (SPoF), and bottlenecks in huge metadata requests.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] One advantage of using HDFS is data awareness between the job tracker and task tracker.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The job tracker schedules map or reduce jobs to task trackers with an awareness of the data location.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] For example: if node A contains data (a, b, c) and node X contains data (x, y, z), the job tracker schedules node A to perform map or reduce tasks on (a, b, c) and node X would be scheduled to perform map or reduce tasks on (x, y, z).
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] This reduces the amount of traffic that goes over the network and prevents unnecessary data transfer.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop is used with other file systems, this advantage is not always available.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] This can have a significant impact on job-completion times as demonstrated with data-intensive jobs.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] HDFS was designed for mostly immutable files and may not be suitable for systems requiring concurrent write operations.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] HDFS can be mounted directly with a Filesystem in Userspace (FUSE) virtual file system on Linux and some other Unix systems.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] File access can be achieved through the native Java API, the Thrift API (generates a client in a number of languages e.g.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] C++, Java, Python, PHP, Ruby, Erlang, Perl, Haskell, C#, Cocoa, Smalltalk, and OCaml), the command-line interface, the HDFS-UI web application over HTTP, or via 3rd-party network client libraries.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] HDFS is designed for portability across various hardware platforms and for compatibility with a variety of underlying operating systems.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The HDFS design introduces portability limitations that result in some performance bottlenecks, since the Java implementation cannot use features that are exclusive to the platform on which HDFS is running.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Due to its widespread integration into enterprise-level infrastructure, monitoring HDFS performance at scale has become an increasingly important issue.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Monitoring end-to-end performance requires tracking metrics from datanodes, namenodes, and the underlying operating system.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] There are currently several monitoring platforms to track HDFS performance, including Hortonworks, Cloudera, and Datadog.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Hadoop works directly with any distributed file system that can be mounted by the underlying operating system by simply using a `file://` URL; however, this comes at a price – the loss of locality.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] To reduce network traffic, Hadoop needs to know which servers are closest to the data, information that Hadoop-specific file system bridges can provide.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] A number of third-party file system bridges have also been written, none of which are currently in Hadoop distributions.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] However, some commercial distributions of Hadoop ship with an alternative file system as the default – specifically IBM and MapR.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Atop the file systems comes the MapReduce Engine, which consists of one *JobTracker*, to which client applications submit MapReduce jobs.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The JobTracker pushes work to available *TaskTracker* nodes in the cluster, striving to keep the work as close to the data as possible.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] With a rack-aware file system, the JobTracker knows which node contains the data, and which other machines are nearby.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] If the work cannot be hosted on the actual node where the data resides, priority is given to nodes in the same rack.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] This reduces network traffic on the main backbone network.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] If a TaskTracker fails or times out, that part of the job is rescheduled.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The TaskTracker on each node spawns a separate Java virtual machine (JVM) process to prevent the TaskTracker itself from failing if the running job crashes its JVM.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] A heartbeat is sent from the TaskTracker to the JobTracker every few minutes to check its status.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The Job Tracker and TaskTracker status and information is exposed by Jetty and can be viewed from a web browser.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] If one TaskTracker is very slow, it can delay the entire MapReduce job – especially towards the end, when everything can end up waiting for the slowest task.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] With speculative execution enabled, however, a single task can be executed on multiple slave nodes.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] By default Hadoop uses FIFO scheduling, and optionally 5 scheduling priorities to schedule jobs from a work queue.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] In version 0.19 the job scheduler was refactored out of the JobTracker, while adding the ability to use an alternate scheduler (such as the *Fair scheduler* or the *Capacity scheduler*, described next).
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler was developed by Facebook.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The goal of the fair scheduler is to provide fast response times for small jobs and quality of service (QoS) for production jobs.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler has three basic concepts.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Each pool is assigned a guaranteed minimum share.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] By default, jobs that are uncategorized go into a default pool.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Pools have to specify the minimum number of map slots, reduce slots, as well as a limit on the number of running jobs.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler was developed by Yahoo.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler supports several features that are similar to those of the fair scheduler.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Free resources are allocated to queues beyond their total capacity.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Within a queue, a job with a high level of priority has access to the queue's resources.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] There is no preemption once a job is running.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The biggest difference between Hadoop 1 and Hadoop 2 is the addition of YARN (Yet Another Resource Negotiator), which replaced the MapReduce engine in the first version of Hadoop.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] YARN strives to allocate resources to various applications effectively.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] It runs two daemons, which take care of two different tasks: the *resource manager*, which does job tracking and resource allocation to applications, the *application master*, which monitors progress of the execution.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] There are important features provided by Hadoop 3.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] For example, while there is one single *namenode* in Hadoop 2, Hadoop 3, enables having multiple name nodes, which solves the single point of failure problem.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] In Hadoop 3, there are containers working in principle of Docker, which reduces time spent on application development.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] One of the biggest changes is that Hadoop 3 decreases storage overhead with erasure coding.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Also, Hadoop 3 permits usage of GPU hardware within the cluster, which is a very substantial benefit to execute deep learning algorithms on a Hadoop cluster.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The HDFS is not restricted to MapReduce jobs.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] It can be used for other applications, many of which are under development at Apache.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] The list includes the HBase database, the Apache Mahout machine learning system, and the Apache Hive data warehouse.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Theoretically, Hadoop could be used for any workload that is batch-oriented rather than real-time, is very data-intensive, and benefits from parallel processing.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] It can also be used to complement a real-time system, such as lambda architecture, Apache Storm, Flink, and Spark Streaming.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Inc. launched what they claimed was the world's largest Hadoop production application.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Search Webmap is a Hadoop application that runs on a Linux cluster with more than 10,000 cores and produced data that was used in every Yahoo! web search query.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] There are multiple Hadoop clusters at Yahoo! and no HDFS file systems or MapReduce jobs are split across multiple data centers.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Every Hadoop cluster node bootstraps the Linux image, including the Hadoop distribution.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Work that the clusters perform is known to include the index calculations for the Yahoo! search engine.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] In June 2009, Yahoo! made the source code of its Hadoop version available to the open-source community.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] In 2010, Facebook claimed that they had the largest Hadoop cluster in the world with 21 PB of storage.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] In June 2012, they announced the data had grown to 100 PB and later that year they announced that the data was growing by roughly half a PB per day.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] As of 2013, Hadoop adoption had become widespread: more than half of the Fortune 50 companies used Hadoop.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] Influential papers on the birth, growth, and curation of Hadoop and big data processing include: Jeffrey Dean, Sanjay Ghemawat (2004) MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters, Google.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] This paper inspired Doug Cutting to develop an open-source implementation of the Map-Reduce framework.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-hadoop] He named it Hadoop, after his son's toy elephant.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] The open-source project to build Apache Parquet began as a joint effort between Twitter and Cloudera using the record shredding and assembly algorithm as described in Google's Dremel.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] Parquet was designed as an improvement on the Trevni columnar storage format created by Doug Cutting, the creator of Hadoop.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] 'small compartment') refers to a style of decorative flooring and was chosen to "evoke the bottom layer of a database with an interesting layout".
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] The first version, Apache Parquet 1.0, was released in July 2013.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] Since April 27, 2015, Apache Parquet has been a top-level Apache Software Foundation (ASF)-sponsored project.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] Apache Parquet is implemented using the record-shredding and assembly algorithm, which accommodates the complex data structures that can be used to store data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] Apache Parquet is implemented using the Apache Thrift framework, which increases its flexibility; it can work with a number of programming languages like C++, Java, Python, PHP, etc.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] As of August 2015, Parquet supports the big-data-processing frameworks including Apache Hive, Apache Drill, Apache Impala, Apache Crunch, Apache Pig, Cascading, Presto and Apache Spark.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] It is one of the external data formats used by the pandas Python data manipulation and analysis library.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] In Parquet, compression is performed column by column, which enables different encoding schemes to be used for text and integer data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] This strategy also keeps the door open for newer and better encoding schemes to be implemented as they are invented.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] Parquet supports various compression formats: snappy, gzip, LZO, brotli, zstd, and LZ4.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] Parquet has an automatic dictionary encoding enabled dynamically for data with a *small* number of unique values (i.e. below 105) that enables significant compression and boosts processing speed.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] Storage of integers is usually done with dedicated 32 or 64 bits per integer.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] For small integers, packing multiple integers into the same space makes storage more efficient.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] To optimize storage of multiple occurrences of the same value, run-length encoding is used, which is where a single value is stored once along with the number of occurrences.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] Parquet implements a hybrid of bit packing and RLE, in which the encoding switches based on which produces the best compression results.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] This strategy works well for certain types of integer data and combines well with dictionary encoding.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] Parquet is widely used as the underlying file format in modern cloud-based data lake architectures.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] Cloud storage systems such as Amazon S3, Azure Data Lake Storage, and Google Cloud Storage commonly store data in Parquet format due to its efficient columnar representation and retrieval capabilities.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] Data lakehouse frameworks—including Apache Iceberg, Delta Lake, and Apache Hudi —build an additional metadata layer on top of Parquet files to support features such as schema evolution, time-travel queries, and ACID-compliant transactions.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] In these architectures, Parquet files serve as the immutable storage layer while the table formats manage data versioning and transactional integrity.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] Apache Parquet is comparable to RCFile and Optimized Row Columnar (ORC) file formats — all three fall under the category of columnar data storage within the Hadoop ecosystem.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] They all have better compression and encoding with improved read performance at the cost of slower writes.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] In addition to these features, Apache Parquet supports limited schema evolution, i.e., the schema can be modified according to the changes in the data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] It also provides the ability to add new columns and merge schemas that do not conflict.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] Apache Arrow is designed as an in-memory complement to on-disk columnar formats like Parquet and ORC.
[src:apache-parquet-format/apache-parquet] The Arrow and Parquet projects include libraries that allow for reading and writing between the two formats.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:apache-parquet-format/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In information theory, **data compression**, **source coding**, or **bit-rate reduction** is the process of encoding information using fewer bits than the original representation.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Any particular compression is either lossy or lossless.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Lossless compression reduces bits by identifying and eliminating statistical redundancy.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] No information is lost in lossless compression.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Lossy compression reduces bits by removing unnecessary or less important information.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Typically, a device that performs data compression is referred to as an encoder, and one that performs the reversal of the process (decompression) as a decoder.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The process of reducing the size of a data file is often referred to as data compression.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In the context of data transmission, it is called source coding: encoding is done at the source of the data before it is stored or transmitted.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Source coding should not be confused with channel coding, for error detection and correction or line coding, the means for mapping data onto a signal.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Data compression algorithms present a space–time complexity trade-off between the bytes needed to store or transmit information, and the computational resources needed to perform the encoding and decoding.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The design of data compression schemes involves balancing the degree of compression, the amount of distortion introduced (when using lossy data compression), and the computational resources or time required to compress and decompress the data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Lossless data compression algorithms usually exploit statistical redundancy to represent data without losing any information, so that the process is reversible.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Lossless compression is possible because most real-world data exhibits statistical redundancy.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] For example, an image may have areas of color that do not change over several pixels; instead of coding "red pixel, red pixel, ..." the data may be encoded as "279 red pixels".
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] This is a basic example of run-length encoding; there are many schemes to reduce file size by eliminating redundancy.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The Lempel–Ziv (LZ) compression methods are among the most popular algorithms for lossless storage.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] DEFLATE is a variation on LZ optimized for decompression speed and compression ratio, but compression can be slow.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In the mid-1980s, following work by Terry Welch, the Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) algorithm rapidly became the method of choice for most general-purpose compression systems.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] LZW is used in GIF images, programs such as PKZIP, and hardware devices such as modems.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] LZ methods use a table-based compression model where table entries are substituted for repeated strings of data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] For most LZ methods, this table is generated dynamically from earlier data in the input.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The table itself is often Huffman encoded.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Grammar-based codes like this can compress highly repetitive input extremely effectively, for instance, a biological data collection of the same or closely related species, a huge versioned document collection, internet archival, etc.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The basic task of grammar-based codes is constructing a context-free grammar deriving a single string.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Other practical grammar compression algorithms include Sequitur and Re-Pair.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The strongest modern lossless compressors use probabilistic models, such as prediction by partial matching.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The Burrows–Wheeler transform can also be viewed as an indirect form of statistical modelling.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In a further refinement of the direct use of probabilistic modelling, statistical estimates can be coupled to an algorithm called arithmetic coding.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Arithmetic coding is a more modern coding technique that uses the mathematical calculations of a finite-state machine to produce a string of encoded bits from a series of input data symbols.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] It can achieve superior compression compared to other techniques, such as the better-known Huffman algorithm.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] It uses an internal memory state to avoid the need to perform a one-to-one mapping of individual input symbols to distinct representations that use an integer number of bits, and it clears out the internal memory only after encoding the entire string of data symbols.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Arithmetic coding applies especially well to adaptive data compression tasks where the statistics vary and are context-dependent, as it can be easily coupled with an adaptive model of the probability distribution of the input data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] An early example of the use of arithmetic coding was in an optional (but not widely used) feature of the JPEG image coding standard.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] It has since been applied in various other designs including H.263, H.264/MPEG-4 AVC and HEVC for video coding.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Archive software typically has the ability to adjust the "dictionary size", where a larger size demands more random-access memory during compression and decompression, but compresses more strongly, especially on repeating patterns in files' content.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In the late 1980s, digital images became more common, and standards for lossless image compression emerged.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In the early 1990s, lossy compression methods began to be widely used.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In these schemes, some loss of information is accepted as dropping nonessential detail can save storage space.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] There is a corresponding trade-off between preserving information and reducing size.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Lossy data compression schemes are designed based on research on how people perceive the data in question.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] For example, the human eye is more sensitive to subtle variations in luminance than it is to the variations in color.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] JPEG image compression works in part by rounding off nonessential bits of information.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] A number of popular compression formats exploit these perceptual differences, including psychoacoustics for sound, and psychovisuals for images and video.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Most forms of lossy compression are based on transform coding, especially the discrete cosine transform (DCT).
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] It was first proposed in 1972 by Nasir Ahmed, who then developed a working algorithm with T.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Rao in 1973, before introducing it in January 1974.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] DCT is the most widely used lossy compression method, and is used in multimedia formats for images (such as JPEG and HEIF), video (such as MPEG, AVC and HEVC) and audio (such as MP3, AAC and Vorbis).
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Lossy image compression is used in digital cameras, to increase storage capacities.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Similarly, DVDs, Blu-ray and streaming video use lossy video coding formats.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Lossy compression is extensively used in video.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In lossy audio compression, methods of psychoacoustics are used to remove non-audible (or less audible) components of the audio signal.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Compression of human speech is often performed with even more specialized techniques; speech coding is distinguished as a separate discipline from general-purpose audio compression.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Speech coding is used in internet telephony, for example, audio compression is used for CD ripping and is decoded by the audio players.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Lossy compression can cause generation loss.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The theoretical basis for compression is provided by information theory and, more specifically, Shannon's source coding theorem; domain-specific theories include algorithmic information theory for lossless compression and rate–distortion theory for lossy compression.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] These areas of study were essentially created by Claude Shannon, who published fundamental papers on the topic in the late 1940s and early 1950s.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Other topics associated with compression include coding theory and statistical inference.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] There is a close connection between machine learning and compression.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] A system that predicts the posterior probabilities of a sequence given its entire history can be used for optimal data compression (by using arithmetic coding on the output distribution).
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Conversely, an optimal compressor can be used for prediction (by finding the symbol that compresses best, given the previous history).
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] This equivalence has been used as a justification for using data compression as a benchmark for "general intelligence".
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] An alternative view can show compression algorithms implicitly map strings into implicit feature space vectors, and compression-based similarity measures compute similarity within these feature spaces.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] For each compressor C(.) we define an associated vector space ℵ, such that C(.) maps an input string x, corresponding to the vector norm ||~x||.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] An exhaustive examination of the feature spaces underlying all compression algorithms is precluded by space; instead, feature vectors chooses to examine three representative lossless compression methods, LZW, LZ77, and PPM.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] According to AIXI theory, a connection more directly explained in Hutter Prize, the best possible compression of x is the smallest possible software that generates x.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] For example, in that model, a zip file's compressed size includes both the zip file and the unzipping software, since you can not unzip it without both, but there may be an even smaller combined form.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Examples of AI-powered audio/video compression software include NVIDIA Maxine, AIVC.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Examples of software that can perform AI-powered image compression include OpenCV, TensorFlow, MATLAB's Image Processing Toolbox (IPT) and High-Fidelity Generative Image Compression.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In unsupervised machine learning, k-means clustering can be utilized to compress data by grouping similar data points into clusters.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] This technique simplifies handling extensive datasets that lack predefined labels and finds widespread use in fields such as image compression.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Data compression aims to reduce the size of data files, enhancing storage efficiency and speeding up data transmission.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] K-means clustering, an unsupervised machine learning algorithm, is employed to partition a dataset into a specified number of clusters, k, each represented by the centroid of its points.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] This process condenses extensive datasets into a more compact set of representative points.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Particularly beneficial in image and signal processing, k-means clustering aids in data reduction by replacing groups of data points with their centroids, thereby preserving the core information of the original data while significantly decreasing the required storage space.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Large language models (LLMs) are also efficient lossless data compressors on some data sets, as demonstrated by DeepMind's research with the Chinchilla 70B model.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Developed by DeepMind, Chinchilla 70B effectively compressed data, outperforming conventional methods such as Portable Network Graphics (PNG) for images and Free Lossless Audio Codec (FLAC) for audio.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] It achieved compression of image and audio data to 43.4% and 16.4% of their original sizes, respectively.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] There is, however, some reason to be concerned that the data set used for testing overlaps the LLM training data set, making it possible that the Chinchilla 70B model is only an efficient compression tool on data it has already been trained on.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Data compression can be viewed as a special case of data differencing.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] This is the same as considering absolute entropy (corresponding to data compression) as a special case of relative entropy (corresponding to data differencing) with no initial data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The term *differential compression* is used to emphasize the data differencing connection.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Entropy coding originated in the 1940s with the introduction of Shannon–Fano coding, the basis for Huffman coding which was developed in 1950.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Transform coding dates back to the late 1960s, with the introduction of fast Fourier transform (FFT) coding in 1968 and the Hadamard transform in 1969.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] An important image compression technique is the discrete cosine transform (DCT), a technique developed in the early 1970s.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] DCT is the basis for JPEG, a lossy compression format which was introduced by the Joint Photographic Experts Group (JPEG) in 1992.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] JPEG greatly reduces the amount of data required to represent an image at the cost of a relatively small reduction in image quality and has become the most widely used image file format.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Its highly efficient DCT-based compression algorithm was largely responsible for the wide proliferation of digital images and digital photos.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) is a lossless compression algorithm developed in 1984.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] It is used in the GIF format, introduced in 1987.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] DEFLATE, a lossless compression algorithm specified in 1996, is used in the Portable Network Graphics (PNG) format.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Wavelet compression, the use of wavelets in image compression, began after the development of DCT coding.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The JPEG 2000 standard was introduced in 2000.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In contrast to the DCT algorithm used by the original JPEG format, JPEG 2000 instead uses discrete wavelet transform (DWT) algorithms.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] JPEG 2000 technology, which includes the Motion JPEG 2000 extension, was selected as the video coding standard for digital cinema in 2004.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Audio data compression, not to be confused with dynamic range compression, has the potential to reduce the transmission bandwidth and storage requirements of audio data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Audio compression formats compression algorithms are implemented in software as audio codecs.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In both lossy and lossless compression, information redundancy is reduced, using methods such as coding, quantization, DCT and linear prediction to reduce the amount of information used to represent the uncompressed data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Lossy audio compression algorithms provide higher compression and are used in numerous audio applications including Vorbis and MP3.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] These algorithms almost all rely on psychoacoustics to eliminate or reduce fidelity of less audible sounds, thereby reducing the space required to store or transmit them.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The acceptable trade-off between loss of audio quality and transmission or storage size depends upon the application.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] For example, one 640 MB compact disc (CD) holds approximately one hour of uncompressed high fidelity music, less than 2 hours of music compressed losslessly, or 7 hours of music compressed in the MP3 format at a medium bit rate.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] A digital sound recorder can typically store around 200 hours of clearly intelligible speech in 640 MB.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Lossless audio compression produces a representation of digital data that can be decoded to an exact digital duplicate of the original.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Compression ratios are around 50–60% of the original size, which is similar to those for generic lossless data compression.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Lossless codecs use curve fitting or linear prediction as a basis for estimating the signal.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Parameters describing the estimation and the difference between the estimation and the actual signal are coded separately.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] A number of lossless audio compression formats exist.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] See list of lossless codecs for a listing.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Some formats are associated with a distinct system, such as Direct Stream Transfer, used in Super Audio CD and Meridian Lossless Packing, used in DVD-Audio, Dolby TrueHD, Blu-ray and HD DVD.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Some audio file formats feature a combination of a lossy format and a lossless correction; this allows stripping the correction to easily obtain a lossy file.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Such formats include MPEG-4 SLS (Scalable to Lossless), WavPack, and OptimFROG DualStream.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] When audio files are to be processed, either by further compression or for editing, it is desirable to work from an unchanged original (uncompressed or losslessly compressed).
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Processing of a lossily compressed file for some purpose usually produces a final result inferior to the creation of the same compressed file from an uncompressed original.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In addition to sound editing or mixing, lossless audio compression is often used for archival storage, or as master copies.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Lossy audio compression is used in a wide range of applications.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In addition to standalone audio-only applications of file playback in MP3 players or computers, digitally compressed audio streams are used in most video DVDs, digital television, streaming media on the Internet, satellite and cable radio, and increasingly in terrestrial radio broadcasts.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Lossy compression typically achieves far greater compression than lossless compression, by discarding less-critical data based on psychoacoustic optimizations.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Psychoacoustics recognizes that not all data in an audio stream can be perceived by the human auditory system.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Most lossy compression reduces redundancy by first identifying perceptually irrelevant sounds, that is, sounds that are very hard to hear.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Typical examples include high frequencies or sounds that occur at the same time as louder sounds.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Those irrelevant sounds are coded with decreased accuracy or not at all.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Due to the nature of lossy algorithms, audio quality suffers a digital generation loss when a file is decompressed and recompressed.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] This makes lossy compression unsuitable for storing the intermediate results in professional audio engineering applications, such as sound editing and multitrack recording.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] However, lossy formats such as MP3 are very popular with end-users as the file size is reduced to 5-20% of the original size and a megabyte can store about a minute's worth of music at adequate quality.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Several proprietary lossy compression algorithms have been developed that provide higher quality audio performance by using a combination of lossless and lossy algorithms with adaptive bit rates and lower compression ratios.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Examples include aptX, LDAC, LHDC, MQA and SCL6.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] To determine what information in an audio signal is perceptually irrelevant, most lossy compression algorithms use transforms such as the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) to convert time domain sampled waveforms into a transform domain, typically the frequency domain.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Once transformed, component frequencies can be prioritized according to how audible they are.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Equal-loudness contours may also be used to weigh the perceptual importance of components.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Models of the human ear-brain combination incorporating such effects are often called psychoacoustic models.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Other types of lossy compressors, such as the linear predictive coding (LPC) used with speech, are source-based coders.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] LPC uses a model of the human vocal tract to analyze speech sounds and infer the parameters used by the model to produce them moment to moment.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] These changing parameters are transmitted or stored and used to drive another model in the decoder, which reproduces the sound.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Lossy formats are often used for the distribution of streaming audio or interactive communication (such as in cell phone networks).
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In such applications, the data must be decompressed as the data flows, rather than after the entire data stream has been transmitted.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Not all audio codecs can be used for streaming applications.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Latency is introduced by the methods used to encode and decode the data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Some codecs will analyze a longer segment, called a *frame*, of the data to optimize efficiency, and then code it in a manner that requires a larger segment of data at one time to decode.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The inherent latency of the coding algorithm can be critical; for example, when there is a two-way transmission of data, such as with a telephone conversation, significant delays may seriously degrade the perceived quality.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In contrast to the speed of compression, which is proportional to the number of operations required by the algorithm, here latency refers to the number of samples that must be analyzed before a block of audio is processed.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In the minimum case, latency is zero samples (e.g., if the coder/decoder simply reduces the number of bits used to quantize the signal).
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Time domain algorithms such as LPC also often have low latencies, hence their popularity in speech coding for telephony.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In algorithms such as MP3, however, a large number of samples have to be analyzed to implement a psychoacoustic model in the frequency domain, and latency is on the order of 23 ms.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Speech encoding is an important category of audio data compression.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The perceptual models used to estimate what aspects of speech a human ear can hear are generally somewhat different from those used for music.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The range of frequencies needed to convey the sounds of a human voice is normally far narrower than that needed for music, and the sound is normally less complex.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] As a result, speech can be encoded at high quality using a relatively low bit rate.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The earliest algorithms used in speech encoding (and audio data compression in general) were the A-law algorithm and the μ-law algorithm.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Early audio research was conducted at Bell Labs.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Chapin Cutler filed the patent on differential pulse-code modulation (DPCM).
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In 1973, Adaptive DPCM (ADPCM) was introduced by P.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Perceptual coding was first used for speech coding compression, with linear predictive coding (LPC).
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Initial concepts for LPC date back to the work of Fumitada Itakura (Nagoya University) and Shuzo Saito (Nippon Telegraph and Telephone) in 1966.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Perceptual coding is used by modern audio compression formats such as MP3 and AAC.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Discrete cosine transform (DCT), developed by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Rao in 1974, provided the basis for the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) used by modern audio compression formats such as MP3, Dolby Digital, and AAC.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Bradley in 1987, following earlier work by Princen and Bradley in 1986.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The world's first commercial broadcast automation audio compression system was developed by Oscar Bonello, an engineering professor at the University of Buenos Aires.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] This broadcast automation system was launched in 1987 under the name Audicom.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] A literature compendium for a large variety of audio coding systems was published in the IEEE's *Journal on Selected Areas in Communications* (*JSAC*), in February 1988.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] While there were some papers from before that time, this collection documented an entire variety of finished, working audio coders, nearly all of them using perceptual techniques and some kind of frequency analysis and back-end noiseless coding.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Uncompressed video requires a very high data rate.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Although lossless video compression codecs perform at a compression factor of 5 to 12, a typical H.264 lossy compression video has a compression factor between 20 and 200.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The two key video compression techniques used in video coding standards are the DCT and motion compensation (MC).
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Most video coding standards, such as the H.26x and MPEG formats, typically use motion-compensated DCT video coding (block motion compensation).
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Most video codecs are used alongside audio compression techniques to store the separate but complementary data streams as one combined package using so-called *container formats*.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Video data may be represented as a series of still image frames.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Such data usually contains abundant amounts of spatial and temporal redundancy.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Video compression algorithms attempt to reduce redundancy and store information more compactly.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Most video compression formats and codecs exploit both spatial and temporal redundancy (e.g., through difference coding with motion compensation).
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Similarities can be encoded by only storing differences between e.g., temporally adjacent frames (inter-frame coding) or spatially adjacent pixels (intra-frame coding).
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Inter-frame compression (a temporal delta encoding) (re)uses data from one or more earlier or later frames in a sequence to describe the current frame.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Intra-frame coding, on the other hand, uses only data from within the current frame, effectively being still-image compression.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The intra-frame video coding formats used in camcorders and video editing employ simpler compression that uses only intra-frame prediction.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] This simplifies video editing software, as it prevents a situation in which a compressed frame refers to data that the editor has deleted.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Usually, video compression additionally employs lossy compression techniques like quantization that reduce aspects of the source data that are (more or less) irrelevant to the human visual perception by exploiting perceptual features of human vision.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] For example, small differences in color are more difficult to perceive than are changes in brightness.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Compression algorithms can average a color across these similar areas in a manner similar to those used in JPEG image compression.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] As in all lossy compression, there is a trade-off between video quality and bit rate, cost of processing the compression and decompression, and system requirements.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Highly compressed video may present visible or distracting artifacts.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Other methods other than the prevalent DCT-based transform formats, such as fractal compression, matching pursuit and the use of a discrete wavelet transform (DWT), have been the subject of some research, but are typically not used in practical products.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Wavelet compression is used in still-image coders and video coders without motion compensation.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Interest in fractal compression seems to be waning, due to recent theoretical analysis showing a comparative lack of effectiveness of such methods.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In inter-frame coding, individual frames of a video sequence are compared from one frame to the next, and the video compression codec records the differences to the reference frame.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] If the frame contains areas where nothing has moved, the system can simply issue a short command that copies that part of the previous frame into the next one.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] If sections of the frame move in a simple manner, the compressor can emit a (slightly longer) command that tells the decompressor to shift, rotate, lighten, or darken the copy.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] This longer command still remains much shorter than data generated by intra-frame compression.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Usually, the encoder will also transmit a residue signal which describes the remaining, more subtle differences to the reference imagery.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Using entropy coding, these residue signals have a more compact representation than the full signal.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In areas of video with more motion, the compression must encode more data to keep up with the larger number of pixels that are changing.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Commonly, the high-frequency detail of explosions, flames, flocks of animals, and some panning shots will lead to decreases in quality or increases in the variable bitrate.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Many commonly used video compression methods (e.g., those in standards approved by the ITU-T or ISO) share the same basic architecture that dates back to H.261, which was standardized in 1988 by the ITU-T.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] They mostly rely on the DCT, applied to rectangular blocks of neighboring pixels, and temporal prediction using motion vectors, as well as nowadays also an in-loop filtering step.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In the prediction stage, various deduplication and difference-coding techniques are applied that help decorrelate data and describe new data based on already transmitted data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Then, rectangular blocks of remaining pixel data are transformed to the frequency domain.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In the main lossy processing stage, frequency domain data gets quantized in order to reduce information that is irrelevant to human visual perception.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In the last stage, statistical redundancy gets largely eliminated by an entropy coder, which often applies some form of arithmetic coding.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In an additional in-loop filtering stage, various filters can be applied to the reconstructed image signal.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] By computing these filters also inside the encoding loop, they can help compression because they can be applied to reference material before it gets used in the prediction process and they can be guided using the original signal.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The most popular example are deblocking filters that blur out blocking artifacts from quantization discontinuities at transform block boundaries.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Cherry proposed a run-length encoding bandwidth compression scheme for the transmission of analog television signals.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The DCT, which is fundamental to modern video compression, was introduced by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] H.261, which debuted in 1988, commercially introduced the prevalent basic architecture of video compression technology.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] It was the first video coding format based on DCT compression.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] H.261 was developed by a number of companies, including Hitachi, PictureTel, NTT, BT and Toshiba.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] The most popular video coding standards used for codecs have been the MPEG standards.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] MPEG-1 was developed by the Motion Picture Experts Group (MPEG) in 1991, and it was designed to compress VHS-quality video.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] It was succeeded in 1994 by MPEG-2/H.262, which was developed by a number of companies, primarily Sony, Thomson and Mitsubishi Electric.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] MPEG-2 became the standard video format for DVD and SD digital television.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] It was also developed by a number of companies, primarily Mitsubishi Electric, Hitachi and Panasonic.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] H.264/MPEG-4 AVC was developed in 2003 by a number of organizations, primarily Panasonic, Godo Kaisha IP Bridge and LG Electronics.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] AVC commercially introduced the modern context-adaptive binary arithmetic coding (CABAC) and context-adaptive variable-length coding (CAVLC) algorithms.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Genetics compression algorithms are the latest generation of lossless algorithms that compress data (typically sequences of nucleotides) using both conventional compression algorithms and genetic algorithms adapted to the specific datatype.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] In 2012, a team of scientists from Johns Hopkins University published a genetic compression algorithm that does not use a reference genome for compression.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] HAPZIPPER was tailored for HapMap data and achieves over 20-fold compression (95% reduction in file size), providing 2- to 4-fold better compression and is less computationally intensive than the leading general-purpose compression utilities.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] For this, Chanda, Elhaik, and Bader introduced MAF-based encoding (MAFE), which reduces the heterogeneity of the dataset by sorting SNPs by their minor allele frequency, thus homogenizing the dataset.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] Other algorithms developed in 2009 and 2013 (DNAZip and GenomeZip) have compression ratios of up to 1200-fold—allowing 6 billion basepair diploid human genomes to be stored in 2.5 megabytes (relative to a reference genome or averaged over many genomes).
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] It is estimated that the total amount of data that is stored on the world's storage devices could be further compressed with existing compression algorithms by a remaining average factor of 4.5:1.
[src:apache-parquet-format/data-compression] It is estimated that the combined technological capacity of the world to store information provides 1,300 exabytes of hardware digits in 2007, but when the corresponding content is optimally compressed, this only represents 295 exabytes of Shannon information.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] The **nested set model** is a technique for representing nested set collections (also known as trees or hierarchies) in relational databases.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] It is based on Nested Intervals, that "are immune to hierarchy reorganization problem, and allow answering ancestor path hierarchical queries algorithmically — without accessing the stored hierarchy relation".
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] The standard relational algebra and relational calculus, and the SQL operations based on them, are unable to express directly all desirable operations on hierarchies.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] The nested set model is a solution to that problem.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] An alternative solution is the expression of the hierarchy as a parent-child relation.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] Joe Celko called this the adjacency list model.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] If the hierarchy can have arbitrary depth, the adjacency list model does not allow the expression of operations such as comparing the contents of hierarchies of two elements, or determining whether an element is somewhere in the subhierarchy of another element.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] When the hierarchy is of fixed or bounded depth, the operations are possible, but expensive, due to the necessity of performing one relational join per level.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] This is often known as the bill of materials problem.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] Hierarchies may be expressed easily by switching to a graph database.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] When these solutions are not available or not feasible, another approach must be taken.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] The nested set model is to number the nodes according to a tree traversal, which visits each node twice, assigning numbers in the order of visiting, and at both visits.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] This leaves two numbers for each node, which are stored as two attributes.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] Querying becomes inexpensive: hierarchy membership can be tested by comparing these numbers.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] Updating requires renumbering and is therefore expensive.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] Refinements that use rational numbers instead of integers can avoid renumbering, and so are faster to update, although much more complicated.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] The "Clothing" category, with the highest position in the hierarchy, encompasses all subordinating categories.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] It is therefore given left and right domain values of 1 and 22, the latter value being the double of the total number of nodes being represented.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] The next hierarchical level contains "Men's" and "Women's", both containing levels within themselves that must be accounted for.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] Each level's data node is assigned left and right domain values according to the number of sublevels contained within, as shown in the table data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] Queries using nested sets can be expected to be faster than queries using a stored procedure to traverse an adjacency list, and so are the faster option for databases which lack native recursive query constructs, such as MySQL 5.x.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] However, recursive SQL queries can be expected to perform comparably for 'find immediate descendants' queries, and much faster for other depth search queries, and so are the faster option for databases which provide them, such as PostgreSQL, Oracle, and Microsoft SQL Server.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] MySQL used to lack recursive query constructs but added such features in version 8.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] The use case for a dynamic endless database tree hierarchy is rare.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] The Nested Set model is appropriate where the tree element and one or two attributes are the only data, but is a poor choice when more complex relational data exists for the elements in the tree.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] Given an arbitrary starting depth for a category of 'Vehicles' and a child of 'Cars' with a child of 'Mercedes', a foreign key table relationship must be established unless the tree table is natively non-normalized.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] Attributes of a newly created tree item may not share all attributes with a parent, child or even a sibling.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] If a foreign key table is established for a table of 'Plants' attributes, no integrity is given to the child attribute data of 'Trees' and its child 'Oak'.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] Therefore, in each case of an item inserted into the tree, a foreign key table of the item's attributes must be created for all but the most trivial of use cases.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] For more complex systems, hierarchy can be developed through relational models rather than an implicit numeric tree structure.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] Depth of an item is simply another attribute rather than the basis for an entire DB architecture.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] The model doesn't allow for multiple parent categories.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] For example, an 'Oak' could be a child of 'Tree-Type', but also 'Wood-Type'.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] An additional tagging or taxonomy has to be established to accommodate this, again leading to a design more complex than a straightforward fixed model.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] Nested sets are very slow for inserts because it requires updating left and right domain values for all records in the table after the insert.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] This can cause a lot of database stress as many rows are rewritten and indexes rebuilt.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] However, if it is possible to store a forest of small trees in table instead of a single big tree, the overhead may be significantly reduced, since only one small tree must be updated.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] The nested interval model does not suffer from this problem, but is more complex to implement, and is not as well known.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] It still suffers from the relational foreign-key table problem.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] The nested interval model stores the position of the nodes as rational numbers expressed as quotients (n/d).
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] Using the nested set model as described above has some performance limitations during certain tree traversal operations.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] The query will be more complicated when searching for children more than one level deep.
[src:apache-parquet-format/nested-set-model] To overcome this limitation and simplify tree traversal an additional column is added to the model to maintain the depth of a node within a tree.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Therefore, remote method call architectures such as CORBA define their serialization formats in detail.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Many institutions, such as archives and libraries, attempt to future proof their backup archives—in particular, database dumps—by storing them in some relatively human-readable serialized format.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] The Xerox Network Systems Courier technology in the early 1980s influenced the first widely adopted standard.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Sun Microsystems published the External Data Representation (XDR) in 1987.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] XDR is an open format, and standardized as STD 67 (RFC 4506) by IETF.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] In the late 1990s, a push to provide an alternative to the standard serialization protocols started: XML, an SGML subset, was used to produce a human-readable text-based encoding.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Such an encoding can be useful for persistent objects that may be read and understood by humans or communicated to other systems regardless of programming language.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] It has the disadvantage of losing the more compact, byte-stream-based encoding, but by this point larger storage and transmission capacities made file size less of a concern than in the early days of computing.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] In the 2000s, XML was often used for asynchronous transfer of structured data between client and server in Ajax web applications.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] XML is an open format and standardized as a W3C recommendation.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] JSON is a lightweight plain-text alternative to XML and is also commonly used for client-server communication in web applications.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] JSON is based on JavaScript syntax but is independent of JavaScript and supported in many other programming languages.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] YAML is a strict superset of JSON and includes additional features such as a data type tags, support for cyclic data structures, indentation-sensitive syntax, and multiple forms of scalar data quoting.
