[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] In Haskell, serialization is supported for types that are members of the Read and Show type classes.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Every type that is a member of the `Read` type class defines a function that will extract the data from the string representation of the dumped data.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] The `Show` type class, in turn, contains the `show` function from which a string representation of the object can be generated.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] The programmer need not define the functions explicitly—merely declaring a type to be deriving Read or deriving Show, or both, can make the compiler generate the appropriate functions for many cases (but not all: function types, for example, cannot automatically derive Show or Read).
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] The auto-generated instance for Show also produces valid source code, so the same Haskell value can be generated by running the code produced by show in, for example, a Haskell interpreter.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] For more efficient serialization, there are haskell libraries that allow high-speed serialization in binary format, e.g. binary.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Java provides automatic serialization which requires that the object be marked by implementing the `java.io.Serializable` interface.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Implementing the interface marks the class as "okay to serialize", and Java then handles serialization internally.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] There are no serialization methods defined on the `Serializable` interface, but a serializable class can optionally define methods with certain special names and signatures that if defined, will be called as part of the serialization/deserialization process.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] The language also allows the developer to override the serialization process more thoroughly by implementing another interface, the `Externalizable` interface, which includes two special methods that are used to save and restore the object's state.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] There are three primary reasons why objects are not serializable by default and must implement the `Serializable` interface to access Java's serialization mechanism.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Firstly, not all objects capture useful semantics in a serialized state.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] For example, a `Thread` object is tied to the state of the current JVM.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] There is no context in which a deserialized `Thread` object would maintain useful semantics.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Secondly, the serialized state of an object forms part of its class' compatibility contract.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Maintaining compatibility between versions of serializable classes requires additional effort and consideration.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Therefore, making a class serializable needs to be a deliberate design decision and not a default condition.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Lastly, serialization allows access to non-transient private members of a class that are not otherwise accessible.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Classes containing sensitive information (for example, a password) should not be serializable nor externalizable.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] The standard encoding method uses a recursive graph-based translation of the object's class descriptor and serializable fields into a byte stream.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Primitives as well as non-transient, non-static referenced objects are encoded into the stream.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Each object that is referenced by the serialized object via a field that is not marked as `transient` must also be serialized; and if any object in the complete graph of non-transient object references is not serializable, then serialization will fail.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] The developer can influence this behavior by marking objects as transient, or by redefining the serialization for an object so that some portion of the reference graph is truncated and not serialized.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] Java does not use constructor to serialize objects.
[src:apache-parquet-format/serialization] It is possible to serialize Java objects through JDBC and store them into a database.
